  "markdown": "[Skip to content](https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2026/04/official-white-house-app-developer-also-a-ufo-conspiracy-theorist/#main)\n\nText\nsettings\n\nStory text\n\nSizeSmallStandardLargeWidth\n\\*StandardWideLinksStandardOrange\n\n\\\\* Subscribers only\n\n[Learn more](https://arstechnica.com/store/product/subscriptions/)\n\nMinimize to nav\n\n\nOn March 27, the White House [announced](https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2026/03/new-white-house-app-delivers-unparalleled-access-to-the-trump-administration/) a “powerful new official mobile app,” calling it “the fastest, most powerful way to stay informed and engaged with the Trump Administration.”\n\nWhile armchair [developers](https://blog.thereallo.dev/blog/decompiling-the-white-house-app) and [infosec experts](https://www.atomic.computer/blog/white-house-app-security-analysis/) have questioned some of the app’s technical design choices, a [former FBI intelligence analyst](https://hax4libre.com/jokers-wild/) uncovered an unusual fact: The small business owner behind the White House app has a side hobby as a conspiracy theorist.\n\nThe White House app was created by [45Press](https://45press.com/), a company based in Canfield, Ohio, a town of fewer than 8,000 people located roughly halfway between Cleveland and Pittsburgh. (Donald Trump was the 45th president of the United States.) The company’s website describes it as a “design, development, and DevOps agency” and a WordPress VIP Agency Partner; it lists Amazon, NBC, and Sony as past clients.\n\n[According to his own X account](https://x.com/joelkendall), the CEO of 45Press, Joel Kendall, has a “hobby” running a social media presence and store under the name “Sir Storia,” which he calls “a website directory of historical and paranormal locations. If it was historical, paranormal or unexplained, we want it added!”\n\nIn August 2025, Kendall [created](https://www.facebook.com/joelkendall/posts/pfbid024QDBQUQnw2TDm6qWfBJdqMhnevyn63Annrh3Em1KUkePxRuvp4LtUvsDhhzpxMdjl) a (now-defunct) online store offering T-shirts for sale of what he called “the most famous UFO events that ever happened in Ohio.” In a Facebook post, Kendall said he hoped his shop would be “the @walmart for UFOs, UAPs, Aliens, Paranormal and much more!”\n\nHis first T-shirt was about the [Trumbull, Ohio, “UFO incident” in 1994](https://www.ufoinsight.com/ufos/close-encounters/trumbull-county-ufo). “If you’re a believer do you \\[sic\\] part for disclosure and get a shirt!” Kendall wrote.\n\n![Picture of a T-shirt design.](https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/45press.jpg)\n\nOne of Kendall’s T-shirt designs.\n\n\nOne of Kendall’s T-shirt designs.\n\n\n\nKendall has also put out multiple YouTube videos with titles like “ [Are Aliens and UFOs real? PROVE ME WRONG!](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NiFKTXHJvfo&ref=hax4libre.com)” and “ [Did Nazis escape on a UFO?](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XnTu9dYCOQ0)”\n\nAs of Tuesday afternoon, the “Aliens” video is no longer on YouTube. The “Nazis” video was recently “ [removed by the uploader](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XnTu9dYCOQ0),” according to the YouTube listing, and was [deleted](https://x.com/sirstoria/status/1975082319485837749) from Kendall’s Twitter account. Social media accounts under both the Sir Storia name and Kendall’s name have either been made private or deleted.\n\nNeither Kendall nor the White House responded to Ars’ request for comment.\n\n[OrangeSlices.ai](http://orangeslices.ai/), a website that tracks government contracting, [noted](https://orangeslices.ai/45press-beats-out-10-to-win-whitehouse-gov-support-contract/) in February that 45Press beat out 10 other companies for the contract. According to the government’s [Request for Quotation](https://govtribe.com/file/government-file/11316026q0002oas-sol-11316026q0002oas-12112025-dot-pdf), the contract was for “Web hosting and development professional services” and required a firm that has a “WordPress CMS partner level of Silver or higher.”\n\nFederal records show that the Executive Office of the President has so far [obligated](https://www.usaspending.gov/award/CONT_AWD_11316026P0005OAS_1100_-NONE-_-NONE-) $1.4 million to 45Press for its services, though the contract has the “potential” to reach $8.4 million.\n\n[115 Comments](https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2026/04/official-white-house-app-developer-also-a-ufo-conspiracy-theorist/#comments \"115 comments\")\n\nComments\n\n\n[Forum view](https://arstechnica.com/civis/threads/official-white-house-app-developer-also-a-ufo-conspiracy-theorist.1512381/)\n\n![Loading](https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/themes/ars-v9/public/images/firework-loader.75ab30.gif)\nLoading comments...\n\n\n[Prev story](https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2026/04/grok-degrades-women-with-vulgar-roasts-swiss-govt-officials-lawsuit-says/ \"Go to: Musk loves Grok’s “roasts.” Swiss official sues in attempt to neuter them.\")\n\n[Next story](https://arstechnica.com/science/2026/04/research-roundup-7-cool-science-stories-we-almost-missed-3/ \"Go to: Research roundup: 7 cool science stories we almost missed\")\n\n1. [![Listing image for first story in Most Read: NASA's Moon ship and rocket seem to be working well, so what about the landers?](https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/NHQ202603240060medium-768x432.jpg)](https://arstechnica.com/space/2026/04/nasas-moon-ship-and-rocket-seem-to-be-working-well-so-what-about-the-landers/)\n\n\n\n\n1. [NASA's Moon ship and rocket seem to be working well, so what about the landers?](https://arstechnica.com/space/2026/04/nasas-moon-ship-and-rocket-seem-to-be-working-well-so-what-about-the-landers/)\n\n2. 2. [Why will today's lunar flyby only beam back low-resolution video?](https://arstechnica.com/space/2026/04/video-from-artemis-ii-flyby-of-the-moon-will-not-initially-look-spectacular/)\n\n3. 3. [“The problem is Sam Altman”: OpenAI Insiders don’t trust CEO](https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2026/04/the-problem-is-sam-altman-openai-insiders-dont-trust-ceo/)\n\n4. 4. [Teardown of unreleased LG Rollable shows why rollable phones aren't a thing](https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2026/04/teardown-of-unreleased-lg-rollable-shows-why-rollable-phones-arent-a-thing/)\n\n5. 5. [\"Cognitive surrender\" leads AI users to abandon logical thinking, research finds](https://arstechnica.com/ai/2026/04/research-finds-ai-users-scarily-willing-to-surrender-their-cognition-to-llms/)\n\n\nCustomize\n\nSign in dialog...",
